<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-035-175 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 475 049</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Oct 14 1991 n342 p22(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Multi standards for multimedia; major vendors join fray over hugepotential market.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Xenakis, John J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A major fight is developing over standards for the nascent marketfor multimedia technology.andP;  The Multimedia PC Marketing Council, aconsortia of 85 firms led by Microsoft Corp, in Oct 1991 announced60 products that support the Multimedia PC (MPC).andP;  The MPC is amicrocomputer with audio board and CD-ROM drive.andP;  It runsMicrosoft Windows and Microsoft's Multimedia Extensions.andO;Multimedia is seen primarily as a consumer technology, but IBMplans to make a big push into the corporate market.andP;  TheIBM-backed Interactive Multimedia Association (IMA) will roll outmany new products in mid-Oct 1991.andP;  IMA products will have greatercapabilities than those supported by the MPC.andP;  For example, IMAproducts will be able to show a television broadcast in the cornerof the computer screen.andP;  IMA members include Apple, Intel Corp,Sony Corp and Eastman Kodak Co.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Standards)International Business Machines Corp. (Standards).andO;Ticker:    IBM; MSFT.andO;Topic:     StandardizationCompetitionProduct DevelopmentComputer industryMultimedia technologyMicrocomputersMultimedia PC Marketing CouncilInteractive Multimedia AssociationConsortia.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>